Project: Explore and Summarize Data - Red Wine Quality

31 Mai 2018

Overview of data set

This tidy data set contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables describing chemical wine properties. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).
In all my study, my dependent variable will be the wine quality. All the other wine properties are considered independent variables analysed to try to predict wine quality.

The data is already in a convenient tidy format.
X is the observation index.
The variables are all listed in separate columns. They are measures of different wine properties for each X observation.
Morevoer, all the variables are numericals (or non categorical):
So on one hand, scatter plots will be quite appropriate to perform bivariate analysis.
On the other hand, there arent any categorical variables. So I wont really get immediately useful insights by performing summary statistics by groups (using group_by), by faceting on categories or with boxplots.
Alternatively one could play with the point size parameter on scatter plots to visualize a third variable. Another possiblity will be to define bins using cut on a choosen continuous variable.
In fact the quality variable is discrete, so it will make sense to use it as color parameter in our plots or to facet on it

To get some first insights on the data, let me now look at the summary statistics

I can already formulate the following observations:

  • Most of the wines have a medium quality.
  • There are no wines of excellent quality.
  • There are no wines of very bad quality.

Due to the number of variables, to help me knowing where to start and decide which variable I want to analyse more in details, let me build first an exhaustive plots matrix using ggpairs. Out of these plots and correlations coeffcient, I note that the following couple variables are significantly correlated (abolsute value of correlation coefficient > 0.3):

  • Negatively:
    • X and density
      Not interesting, X doesnt represent any wine property
    • pH and fixed acidity: -0.683 > makes totally sense: pH is a logarithmic scale to measure pH, 0 being the lowest.
    • volatile acidity and citric acid: -0.552
    • citric acid and pH: -0.542
      High acids proportion (e.g citric acid) means high acidity means low pH.
    • densitiy and alcohol: -0.496
      Alcohol or ethanol has a relatively low density or is quite light: 0.7893 g/cm3. Compared to~1g/cm3 for water. So the higher alcohol % volume, the lower the wine density.
    • density and pH: -0.342
      pH is low because of the acids, which have a high density (see below).
  • Positively:
    • density and fixed acidity: 0.668
      Unlike ethanol the tartaric acid is rather a heavy molecule, density 1.665 g/cm3. So the higher the higher the tartaric acid amount, the higher the acidity, the higher the density.
    • fixed acidity and citric acid: 0.672
      Citric acid being an acid, this relationship is not surprising.
    • citric acid and sulphates: 0.313
    • citric acid and density: 0.365
      Same explaination as for acidity/tartaric acid. Citric acid has a density of 1.665 g/cm3.
    • residual sugar and density: 0.355
      Same exaplaination as for the acids: sugar (both glucose and sucrose have a density higher than 1.5 g/cm3, which is significantly higher than water density (~1 g/cm3).
    • chlorides and sulphates: 0.371
    • free and total sulfur dioxide
      Altough I am not a chemist, I would say that this is no surprise, so i wont consider this as an interesting finding.

So let me focus on the following variables for further analysis:

  • the citric acid
  • the residual sugar

  • the alcohol volume Reasons to select these are that the above correlations showed that:

  • citric acid drives acidity and pH
  • they all drive density (although alcohol and citric acid/residual sugar in different directions)

  • My hinch is that they have a direct influence on the actually perceived wine taste: bitterness/freshness with the acidity brought by citric acid and sweetness brought by residual sugars.

Thinking about taste properties, I miss the a measure describing a salty flavour. So I will add the chlorides measure to the variables I want to analyse.

Now some first questions that I will try to answer are:

  1. Do good wines tend to be:
    • more or less sweet?
    • more or less fresh/bitter?
    • more or less salty?
  2. Or are there both good and bad wines having a particular taste (sweet/fresh/salty)?
  3. What is average alcohol volume of the best wines?

Here despite the decrease for medium quality, I can also see a clear trend: better quality wine tend to have, in average, a higher volume of alcohol.

Let me remind that I just looked at the average. On all these plots we see a high variance for all quality levels: for instance on the third plot, we have wine of quality level 7, which have 9% alcohol (close to the minimum for all wines) but also more than 13% (maximum for all wines).
Lets now look at boxplots to get insights on the median and quartiles.

Here I note the big difference between the median and Q3 on the boxplot of critical.acid vs quality level 3. Same for the residual sugar level. I also see a important number of outliers regarding both residual sugar level and alcohol volume for quality 5 wines. The trends seen on the previous plots are also confirmed. Better wines tend to have:

  • a higher citric.acid concentration
  • a higher volume of alcohol
  • a smaller concetration of chlorides.

Multivariate Analysis

As I couldnt make any conclusions regarding the sugar concentration based on the previous plots, I want to build visualization of sugar level vs quality vs the other variables.

Based on this plots, because of noise" and overplotting, it is still hard to state any clear relationship between sugar level and wine quality. Something interesting though: on the first graph we see that good wines (quality above or equal to 7) with a citric.acid concentration less than 0.3 g/dm3, keep their level of residual sugar between 1 and 3 g/dm3. As soon as the concentration of citric.acid is higher than 0.3, the level of sugar doesnt matter anymore.
Maybe it is because a good wine have to be balanced and maybe a sweet taste can only be balanced by a minimum level of bitterness brought by the citric acid.

Lets try now to reduce the noise:

p5 <- ggplot(data=subset(wine, wine$quality %in% c(3, 4, 7, 8)),
       aes(x = round(residual.sugar/2)*2, y=alcohol)) + 
         geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=mean, aes(color=quality))

p6 <- ggplot(data=subset(wine, wine$quality %in% c(3, 4, 7, 8)),
       aes(x = round(residual.sugar/2)*2, y=chlorides)) + 
         geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=mean, aes(color=quality))

p7 <- ggplot(data=subset(wine, wine$quality %in% c(3, 4, 7, 8)),
       aes(x = round(residual.sugar/2)*2, y=citric.acid)) + 
         geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=mean, aes(color=quality))


grid.arrange(p5, p6, p7, ncol=1)

Summary

Final Plots

I think that reading the previous plots it is possible to define some ranges for the levels of citric.acid, residual.sugar, alcohol and chlorides that help to clearly separate a excellent wine to a bad one.
Note that quality 3 indicates a bad wine and 8 a very good wine.
